"# Appendix C — REPL Survival Guide

The REPL — *Read, Eval, Print, Loop* — is the interactive prompt where you type one expression at a time and watch it evaluate. It's the fastest way to try things, debug things, and explore the language.

Every serious Motoi Scheme programmer keeps a REPL open at all times.

## Starting a REPL

```
$ motoi repl
motoi 0.1.0  —  type ,help <verb> or ,exit
>
```

The `>` is the prompt. Type an expression, press Return.

```
> (+ 3 4)
7
> (display \"hello\")
hello
> (define x 10)
> x
10
```

Values print. `define` binds and prints nothing.

## Setting up your environment

Before hitting the REPL, install Motoi. See Appendix G for pointers.

Basic check that it's installed:

```
$ motoi version
motoi 0.1.0
```

If that works, `motoi repl` will work.

## Meta-commands

Anything starting with a comma is a *meta-command* — it's interpreted by the REPL itself, not evaluated as Scheme.

- `,help` — list all meta-commands.
- `,help <verb>` — full docs for a verb (name, contract, doc, examples).
- `,type <verb>` — the verb's contract, e.g. `(+ number ...) -> number`.
- `,doc <verb>` — just the docstring.
- `,arity <verb>` — number of arguments the verb accepts.
- `,examples <verb>` — tiered examples (novice / intermediate / expert).
- `,apropos <regex>` — every verb whose name matches the regex, grouped by namespace.
- `,expand <expr>` — show the macro-expanded form of an expression.
- `,exit` — leave the REPL.

Example session:

```
> ,help audio/play
audio/play — play a sound. Kind is 'tone, 'note, 'sfx, 'music.
  (audio/play 'tone freq dur) — pure tone in Hz.
  (audio/play 'note pitch dur) — note from name (e.g. \"C4\").
  ...

> ,apropos ^cortex/
cortex/read
cortex/write
cortex/recall
cortex/remember
cortex/keys
cortex/size
cortex/query
cortex/forget

> ,expand (when (> 5 3) (display \"yes\"))
(if (> 5 3) (begin (display \"yes\")) #f)
```

## The three most useful meta-commands

You will use these three constantly:

**`,help`** when you forget a verb's signature.

**`,apropos`** when you can't remember a verb's exact name. `,apropos gr` shows every verb with `gr` in the name — grid, geom, etc.

**`,expand`** when a macro isn't behaving. See what the expander produced.

## Multi-line input

For most short things, one-liners are fine. But when you're defining a function or macro, you'll want to type on multiple lines. The REPL notices unbalanced parentheses and waits.

```
> (define (my-sum lst)
    (if (null? lst)
        0
        (+ (car lst) (my-sum (cdr lst)))))
> (my-sum '(1 2 3 4 5))
15
```

When the last close-paren balances, the REPL evaluates. If you get lost — too many opens or you can't remember what you were writing — hit Ctrl-C to abort the current input and start fresh.

## Recalling history

Up-arrow recalls the previous input. Down-arrow moves forward. Ctrl-R searches (bash-style). This is your best friend when you're iterating on a formula — write, run, up-arrow, tweak, run.

## Copying from files into the REPL

Two ways to load a file's definitions into a live REPL:

**Copy-paste.** Open the file, select all, paste into the REPL. Works fine for small files.

**Load with `motoi run` — inline eval.** More reliable for larger files: exit the REPL, put the definitions in `defs.scm`, and prepend them to whatever script you're writing:

```
$ cat defs.scm my-experiments.scm | motoi run /dev/stdin
```

Until `import` and `load` are wired (see Chapter 15), that's the shape.

## When the REPL crashes

Two common ways to make Motoi's REPL unhappy:

**Fuel exhausted.** You wrote a loop that ran too many times. The interpreter cut off at 200000 steps. Fix: use `--fuel N` (via `motoi --fuel 500000 repl`) or write a smaller test.

**Unbound symbol.** You called a verb Motoi doesn't know. Fix: check spelling, or use `,apropos <substring>` to find the right name.

Neither of these will crash the REPL itself. They print an error and return you to the prompt. Try again.

## When the REPL freezes

If it stops responding — a very long-running audio pattern, an infinite non-tail-recursion — hit Ctrl-C. The REPL should recover. If it doesn't, hit Ctrl-D to exit and restart.

## Best-practices for using the REPL

**Test small.** Before writing a function that does five things, get the five things working one at a time in the REPL.

**Explore verb behavior.** Not sure what `synth/chord` returns? Type `(synth/chord (list \"C4\" \"E4\" \"G4\") 1.0)` in the REPL. The return value tells you.

**Save what worked.** When a REPL session produces a working recipe, copy it into a `.scm` file. The REPL is temporary; files are persistent.

**Use `,help` early.** Every time you meet a new verb, ,help it. Two seconds spent reading the contract saves ten minutes of guessing.

**Watch the pattern.** Every mistake teaches you something about the language. Wrong number of arguments? That's arity — Chapter 6. Type mismatch? That's what predicates are for — Chapter 4. Unexpected `#f`? Read your `if`s.

## Common REPL patterns

**A quick math check.**
```
> (math/sqrt 200)
14.142135623730951
> (* 22 7)
154
```

**Try a formula with different inputs.**
```
> (define (f x) (+ (* 2 x) 1))
> (map f '(0 1 2 3 4 5))
(1 3 5 7 9 11)
```

**Verify a macro expansion.**
```
> ,expand (my-and 1 2 3)
(if 1 (if 2 3 #f) #f)
```

**Check a verb's arity.**
```
> ,arity synth/chord
2
```

**Inspect current cortex.**
```
> (cortex/keys)
(scene/collected greeting name)
> (cortex/size)
3
```

## What the REPL doesn't do (yet)

Some of the meta-commands in the source are *stubs* — they exist as an API surface but don't yet do anything meaningful. As of writing:

- `,trace <fn>` — will record calls once implemented.
- `,untrace <fn>` — pair to `,trace`.
- `,watch <expr>` — re-evaluate on every prompt, printing the result.
- `,inspect <val>` — interactive drill-into a value.

Try them; they'll tell you \",trace: not yet implemented\". No harm done. Watch for future Motoi versions to fill these in.

## What to do first when opening a REPL

The muscle-memory ritual:

1. `motoi repl`
2. Type `(+ 1 1)` — confirm the interpreter is alive.
3. Do whatever brought you here.

If the first two work and the third doesn't, the problem is in *your* code, not in the runtime. Start there. Every time.")
